    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "3c163c5d_fe29e875",
        "filename": "perf/go/regression/regressiontest/regressiontest.go",
        "patchSetId": 7
      },
      "lineNbr": 18,
      "author": {
        "id": 5205
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-02-28T16:02:39Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "The ctx variable is a variable like any other variable, and you haven\u0027t explained why it should be handled differently than any other variable, except for a case where you needed to change it for all tests, which seems like it would be better to have that variable built in just one place so the change can be done once rather than sprinkling it through a bunch of sub-tests.\n\nThis seems like the same category error we made with constants, treating them differently by making them in ALL CAPS, when in fact they are just another identifier and they should be treated the same.",
      "parentUuid": "dd64ccba_2738373e",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 18,
        "startChar": 5,
        "endLine": 18,
        "endChar": 16
      },
      "revId": "812cc92c66452d9ab02c710f919521d52e2ec327",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "d4ab89aa_75d610d6",
        "filename": "perf/go/regression/regressiontest/regressiontest.go",
        "patchSetId": 7
      },
      "lineNbr": 18,
      "author": {
        "id": 5395
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-02-28T16:16:38Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "One thing I am a bit paranoid about is accidental mutations of data. As such, I will generally do\nctx :\u003d context.Background()\nstore.Put(ctx, makeTestCommitDetail())\n...\ncd :\u003d store.Get(ctx, testID)\nassert.Equal(t, makeTestCommitDetail(), cd)\n\nThe reason being that if somehow Put changes the object I gave it (which is a plausible risk here due to the fact that SetLow takes a pointer), I want my assertion to do exactly what I expect. The following might behave strangely (or silently pass) if Put mutates input.\n\nctx :\u003d context.Background()\ninput :\u003d makeTestCommitDetail()\nstore.Put(ctx, input)\n...\ncd :\u003d store.Get(ctx, testID)\nassert.Equal(t, input, cd)\n\nThus I usually make my test generation helpers have one return value, so I can easily slot them in where needed. \n\nYou don\u0027t have to follow that lead, but I find it reassuring to write my tests in this fashion.",
      "parentUuid": "3c163c5d_fe29e875",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 18,
        "startChar": 5,
        "endLine": 18,
        "endChar": 16
      },
      "revId": "812cc92c66452d9ab02c710f919521d52e2ec327",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "f4e0ec9d_23b16f1f",
        "filename": "perf/go/regression/regressiontest/regressiontest.go",
        "patchSetId": 7
      },
      "lineNbr": 31,
      "author": {
        "id": 5395
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-02-28T14:42:25Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "It\u0027s not particularly clear to me why we just make empty structs and return them to be used in a few places and never asserted with or on.\n\nMight it be better to make a helper function storeRegression(ctx, cd, name) and have the helper function initialize the empty structs to be passed into SetLow?\n\nOtherwise, the test reads like state might be loaded into these objects for use later. If that *is* the case, then it should be explicitly called out (and probably some assertions should check that).",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 29,
        "startChar": 0,
        "endLine": 31,
        "endChar": 36
      },
      "revId": "812cc92c66452d9ab02c710f919521d52e2ec327",
